\begin_layout BeginFrame
Birds Exterminated by Brown Treesnake: Ecosystem Services Lost 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Accidentally introduced by U.S.
 Military in late 1940s
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Guam's forest birds are gone because of snake predation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ecosystem services provided by birds also gone: seed dispersal, pollination,
 insectivory
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Overbrowsing by Ungulates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Much of Guam's forest is heavily damaged by deer and pigs which preferentially
 browse on native plants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Especially true on forested land occupied by the military, where hunting
 is prohibited.
 Andersen Air Force Base has deer population densities as high as anywhere
 in the world.
\end_layout

