 micronesica
\emph default
 have been killed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Coconut Palms Attacked by Coconut Rhinoceros Beetle (CRB)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Cocos nucifera
\emph default
 was listed as the 2nd most populous tree-sized plant (DBH>5
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) in the latest forest survey (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Donnegan et al. 2002"
target "http://www.fs.fed.us/pnw/pubs/pnw_rb243.pdf"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CRB was detected on Guam in 2007; adults kill palms by boring into the crown
 to feed on sap
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To date, the CRB infestation has spread to most of central and northern
 Guam
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
50% tree mortality is to be expected if CRB population levels are not kept
 in check
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
And Now the Little Fire Ant? ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Many Invasive Species in Guam's Forests Remain Undetected
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Biological monitoring of Guam's forests is almost non-existent.
 We don't have a biodiversity inventory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Invasive species are almost always discovered accidentally, after establishment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example: After the coffee berry borer (CBB) was discovered in Hawaii, I
 deployed a single CBB trap during Jan and Feb 2011 at a single site in
 a forested area on Guam.
 Trapped bark beetles (Scolytidae) where identified by Dr.
 Don Bright, Colorado State University.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
This single trap, at a single location, caught 7 species of bark beetles
 4 of which were not previously reported from Guam.
\end_layout

